{{Infobox person | name = Annie Rowan Forney Daugette | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = June 1, 1876 | birth_place = | death_date = September 11, 1974 | death_place = | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = American author and historian | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Annie Rowan Forney Daugette''' (June 1, 1876 – September 11, 1974) was an American author and historian. The daughter of a confederate general, she influenced a passage to restore the current [[Seal of Alabama]], and started a resolution to return the flag of the Republic of Alabama back from Iowa. She was inducted into the [[Alabama Women's Hall of Fame]] in 1978.
==Early years== Born on June 1, 1876,<ref>{{cite web|title=Daugette, Annie Rowan Forney, 1876 – 1974|url=http://www.lib.ua.edu/Alabama_Authors/?p=1061|publisher=University of Alabama|accessdate=June 29, 2016}}</ref> Daugette was the daughter of Confederate Major General [[John H. Forney]] and Septima Sexta Middleton, née Rutledge.<ref name=hof>{{cite web|title=Annie Rowan Forney Daugette (1876–1974)|url=http://www.awhf.org/daugette.html|publisher=Alabama Women's Hall of Fame|accessdate=June 29, 2016}}</ref> Her father gained fame for his actions in the [[Siege of Vicksburg]] and for early campaigning within Virginia.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|last=Hall|first=Cody|title=History Plays Vital Role in Life of Mrs. Daugette|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5727499/mrs_daugette_1962/|work=[[The Anniston Star]]|date=September 18, 1962|page=8|via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}}}}</ref> She had one sister, Sabina Forney Stevenson.<ref name=funeral>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Daugette's funeral Friday|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/alabama/anniston/anniston-star/1974/09-12/page-8?tag=annie+rowan+forney+daugette&rtserp=tags/annie-rowan-forney-daugette|work=The Anniston Star|page=8A|date=September 12, 1974|subscription=y|via=[[NewspaperArchive.com]]}}</ref> Daugette grew up in [[Jacksonville, Alabama]], and was educated at [[Jacksonville State University|Jacksonville State Normal School]] (now called Jacksonville State University).<ref name=hof/> She was awarded the [[Elliot Bronze Medal]] in 1894 for creating the best drawing of heads, while attending art class at [[Cooper Union Art School]] and [[National Academy Museum and School]].<ref name=1978times>{{cite news|title=To Be Inducted Into Alabama's Women's Hall of Fame|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=19781022&id=1qcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=V9YEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3017,3378616&hl=en|work=[[Gadsden Times]]|page=2|date=October 23, 1978}}</ref> She married Dr. Clarence William Daugette on December 22, 1897, with whom she had four children and placed dedication towards her family as well as his career.<ref name=hof/>
==Political achievements== Daugette served as president of [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]]'s Alabama division between 1937 and 1939 where she began a campaign to restore the original [[Seal of Alabama|Great Seal of Alabama]] and managed a campaign which resulted in unanimous approval from the 1939 General Assembly of Alabama.<ref name="hof" /> Daugette made alterations to the seal,<ref>{{Cite journal|date=|title=Annie Rowan Forney Daugette|url=http://www.jsu.edu/library/collections/first_hundred_years_collection/Chapter2.pdf|journal=|volume=|issue=|page=29|access-date=July 14, 2016}}</ref> and was later made the Honorary Life President of the United Daughters of the Confederacy on May 10, 1952.<ref name=hof/> She also helped to influence passage of a resolution introduced by Senator [[J. Lister Hill]], designating "The War Between the States" as the proper term for the [[American Civil War]], and this led to her name being entered into the [[Congressional Record]].<ref name=1978times/> Daugette instigated the effort in the return of the long-lost flag of the [[Flag of Alabama|Republic of Alabama]] which was located in Iowa to [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], and later regarded it as one of her greatest achievements.<ref name=funeral/> She additionally helped to donate a large number of books on Alabama and the Southern United States to libraries across Alabama, Daugette also created confederate and US flags which were presented to several organizations across Alabama.<ref name="funeral" /> She was awarded the Honorary Doctor of Humanities by Jacksonville State University in 1970.<ref name=hof/>
==Death and legacy== Daugette died on the morning of September 11, 1974, at [[Piedmont Hospital (Alabama)|Piedmont Hospital]] following a short illness at the age of 98.<ref name=funeral/> On October 26, 1978, Daugette was inducted into the [[Alabama Women's Hall of Fame]], which Jacksonville declared to be "Annie Rowan Forney Daugette Day".<ref name=1978times/> She has been described by ''[[The Anniston Star]]'' as the "[[Betsy Ross]] of Alabama" and as "a true daughter of the Old South";<ref name="funeral" /> she was known by the locals as a "charming hostess" at her Jacksonville home, called "The Magnolias", where she was anxious over its restoration.<ref name="funeral" />
