'''John Wiedhofft Gough''' (23 February 1900 - 1976) was a Welsh historian noted for his study of [[John Locke]]'s political philosophy.
Gough was described as an outstanding student whilst at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], achieving a first in both the classics and modern history, in 1922 and 1923, respectively.<ref>Stuart Brown (ed.), ''Dictionary of Twentieth-Century British Philosophers'' (Bloomsbury, 2005), p. 339.</ref> He was a fellow of [[Oriel College, Oxford]] and in 1947 was appointed lecturer in modern history. He was awarded a DLitt in 1965.<ref>Brown, p. 339.</ref>
==Works== *''The Social Contract: A Critical Study of its Development'' (Oxford University Press, 1936; 2nd ed., 1957). *''John Locke's Political Philosophy: Eight Studies'' (Oxford University Press, 1950; 2nd ed., 1973).
