'''Thomas Heebøll-Holm''' is a [[medieval]] historian at the [[SAXO Institute]] at the [[University of Copenhagen]].  He is most known for his research involving medieval [[knights]] and the possibility that they suffered from [[Post-traumatic stress disorder]] and other hardships.<ref name=Discovery>{{cite news|title=MEDIEVAL KNIGHTS MAY HAVE HAD PTSD|url=http://news.discovery.com/history/medieval-knights-ptsd-111220.html#mkcpgn=rssnws1|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=Discovery.com}}</ref><ref name=Nordic>{{cite news|title=Violent knights feared posttraumatic stress|url=http://sciencenordic.com/violent-knights-feared-posttraumatic-stress|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=Scientific Nordic}}</ref>  In his research, Heeboll-Holm has aimed to apply modern [[military psychology]] on the history of knights, using information gained in recent decades on the psychological effects of war on soldiers.  Heeboll-Holm has studied a number of ancient texts but has focused on three books by [[Geoffroi de Charny]].

'''Heebøll-Holm''' is also known for his work on medieval [[piracy]]. In particular, he has argued that early Danish kings relied in part on piracy to build their political and financial strength.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/denmarks-earliest-kings-were-also-pirates-180956439/?q=|title=Denmark’s Earliest Kings Were Also Pirates|last=Blakemore|first=Erin|work=Smithsonian|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref> He is currently working as an Associate Professor with a PhD. in History at the Centre for Medieval Literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findresearcher.sdu.dk/portal/en/persons/thomas-heeboellholm(85544f3e-c7f6-45b4-9f1b-d1f60de0f5cf).html|title=Thomas Heebøll-Holm - Syddansk Universitet|website=findresearcher.sdu.dk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>

